04061nam a22005535i 9780822376507DE-B159720210202111235.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210202t20142014ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223765077 a10.1515/97808223765072doi  a(DE-B1597)553647  a(OCoLC)875096582  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aHIS0210002bisacsh1 aStolz, Robert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBad Water :bNature, Pollution, and Politics in Japan, 1870-1950 /cRobert Stolz. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b1 table, 8 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAsia-Pacific: Culture, Politics, and Society00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tOne A Decade of Leaks -- tTwo Pollution and Peasants at the Limits of Liberalism -- tThree Nature over Nation -- tFour Natural Democracy -- tFive The Original Green Company -- tConclusion Bad Water, a Theoretical Consideration -- tAppendix Tanaka and Kōtoku's Appeal to the Meiji Emperor -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBad Water is a sophisticated theoretical analysis of Japanese thinkers and activists' efforts to reintegrate the natural environment into Japan's social and political thought in the late nineteenth century and early twentieth. The need to incorporate nature into politics was revealed by a series of large-scale industrial disasters in the 1890s. The Ashio Copper Mine unleashed massive amounts of copper, arsenic, mercury, and other pollutants into surrounding watersheds. Robert Stolz argues that by forcefully demonstrating the mutual penetration of humans and nature, industrial pollution biologically and politically compromised the autonomous liberal subject underlying the political philosophy of the modernizing Meiji state. In the following decades, socialism, anarchism, fascism, and Confucian benevolence and moral economy were marshaled in the search for new theories of a modern political subject and a social organization adequate to the environmental crisis. With detailed considerations of several key environmental activists, including Tanaka Shōzō, Bad Water is a nuanced account of Japan's environmental turn, a historical moment when, for the first time, Japanese thinkers and activists experienced nature as alienated from themselves and were forced to rebuild the connections.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh1 aKōtoku's, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrand, Snow, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTanaka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShōzō's, Tanaka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071182040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822376507zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822376507423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822376507.jpg  a978-3-11-071182-0  DUK eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles